The Telegraph - Calcutta : Sport
		 Saturday, June 26, 2004  BRIEFS
				 																																	Buenos Aires: Diego Maradona has shed over 20 kgs (44 pounds) since being hospitalised in Argentina for cocaine addiction. His personal doctor Alfredo Cahe told local radio on Thursday that the Argentina World Cup winner, who tipped the scales at over 100 kgs (220 pounds) before going into hospital, had lost between 20 and 21.5 kgs.				 																																	Cahe added that Maradona would return to Cuba, where he has spent most of the past four years undergoing a drugs rehabilitation programme, when his health improves. Maradona, 43, is being treated at a psychiatric clinic in the suburbs of Buenos Aires.				 																																	Lagos: Shaktar Donetsk forward Julius Aghahowa has pulled out of Nigerias squad for their World Cup qualifier against Algeria on July 3 due to a leg injury. Aghahowa told me he is yet to fully recover from the leg injury that has kept him out of action and will miss the Algeria game, Nigerian FA secretary-general Taiwo Ogunjobi said on Friday.				 																																	The Ukraine-based striker had not played for Nigeria since the 2004 African Nations Cup in Tunisia, where they lost in the semi-finals to the hosts and eventual winners. He had been included on Wednesday in Nigerias 22-strong squad for the qualifier.				 																																	London: Germanys Ralf Schumacher remains doubtful for the French GP on July 4 and a decision on his participation will be taken early next week, his Williams Formula One team said on Friday. Schumacher spun and crashed heavily into a concrete wall during last Sundays US Grand Prix.				 																																	As its only been four days since I was released from hospital, I cannot at this stage make a decision as to whether I will take part in next weekends race in Magny-Cours, he said on Friday.				 																																	New Delhi: Former Olympians including Md Shahid, Ashok Kumar and Zafar Iqbal would be seen in action in an exhibition hockey match against a womens team, comprising members of the Indian team, for the benefit of former international Vivek Singh, who is battling cancer. The funds collected from the July 7 match, being organised by the Hockey Journalists Association, would be given to the ailing hockey star for his treatment.Paris: World time trial champion David Millar of Britain admitted during 48 hours of police custody to using the banned blood booster EPO, lEquipe claimed on Friday. The daily said empty phials of EPO were found when police searched his home after detaining the Scottish rider in Biarritz. The newspaper, without citing any sources, said the 27-year-old would be charged with illegal possession of toxic products. Millars Cofidis team has been under investigation since January.Sport on Screen Tennis, Wimbledon: Live from 4.30 pm on STAR Sports 
